The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                               The City Diary
                Two engineering aspirants were arrested during the counselling of joint entrance rank-holders at Salt Lake stadium on Sunday for allegedly forging their rank cards. Arijit Mondol, a 19-year-old resident of Durgapur who could not crack the examination, allegedly produced a fake rank card. Sushovan Maji, an 18-year-old resident of Haldia, tampered with his rank card to improve his position, said an officer of Bidhannagar South police station. Both youths claimed our system was faulty but soon broke down, said an official of the board. Deep Roy, who was arrested on Saturday for tampering with his JEE rank card, was produced in court on Sunday and remanded in police custody.    Three members of a gang that used children to rob mobile phone shops at night were arrested in Beniapukur on Saturday. The trio were involved in several thefts in south Calcutta. During interrogation, they confessed to using slum children aged between 12 and 15 years for robberies at night, said a police officer. The racket came to light after a recent robbery in a mobile phone shop near Park Circus No. 4 bridge. According to police, 10 to 15 people are involved in the racket.     National Security Guard personnel conducted a routine check in and around Writers Buildings for two-and-a-half-hours from 7.20am on Sunday. The commandos checked the entrances and exits, the corridor leading to the chief ministers chamber and the chamber itself.    Two youths who were allegedly part of the gang that looted a postal department van on June 30 at Gandhimore in Titagarh were arrested on Saturday night. Guddu Rao, 27, and Pintu Das, 30, were picked up from a hideout in Titagarh. Police said Guddu was driving the van in which the men escaped.    Yasin Mullick, 50, and Sheikh Bapi, 32, died after the bombs they were allegedly making exploded in a cowshed in Uluberia on Sunday morning. The explosion blew off the two as well as the shed. The bodies were found near an adjacent pond.    About 30 residents of Bankrahat, near Thakurpukur, fell ill on Sunday afternoon allegedly after drinking water distributed by the Calcutta Municipal Corporation. They were taken to Vidyasagar Hospital in Behala. Five persons had to be admitted.    Shibaji Sengupta, the branch-in-charge of dud IT firm Assurgent Technology Solutions Private Limited, was arrested late on Saturday. Cops are on the lookout for seven other officials of the company for duping its 1,800-odd employees. Sengupta was produced in court on Sunday and remanded in police custody for three days.    A poster with Maoist slogans was found on the wall of a club in Sodepur on Sunday.                                                                                                                                                                   
